title: Tesla enters into agreement with Chinese lenders for Shanghai Gigafactory
text: Tesla Inc said on Thursday it signed an agreement with lenders in China for a 12-month facility of up to 3.5 billion yuan ($521.36 million) for its Gigafactory in Shanghai.

title: Elon Musk asks Pentagon for his security clearance back during review of pot-smoking incident
text: Musk, who is also CEO of Tesla, refiled security form SF-86, the person said, following his apparent use of marijuana on a podcast last year, which the U.S. Air Force began looking into in September.

title: Pentagon Said to Review Elon Musk's Federal Security Clearance
text: The Pentagon is reviewing Elon Musk’s federal security clearance following the billionaire’s marijuana toke on a California comedian’s podcast in September, according to a U.S. official. Bloomberg's Bill Faries has more on "Bloomberg Markets: The Close."

title: Today's Pickup: Tesla's New Charging Stations Can Charge Cars In Around 15 Minutes
text: Tesla Inc (TSLA) is in the midst of updating its charging stations to accommodate double the power as before.

title: Did Audi Just Disrupt Tesla's Model Y?
text: Audi's e-tron Q4 Concept is aimed squarely at the upcoming new Tesla -- and it looks good.

title: Demand for Tesla's "Impressive" Model 3 Will Be There, Tigress CIO Says
text: Ivan Feinseth, chief investment officer of Tigress Financial Partners, Bloomberg Businessweek's Max Chafkin and Bloomberg's Craig Trudell discuss the outlook for demand for Tesla Inc.'s Model 3 with Bloomberg's Emily Chang on "Bloomberg Technology."

title: Buying More Tesla For My Bear Market Portfolio
text: Trading sales reps for a lower price is a good idea worth testing in my book. I have confidence that management will make adjustments if needed. This is not going to be the reason Tesla fails as so many journalists suggest. That's why this is a good time to add to my position.

title: Tesla's Problems In China Highlight Its Biggest Threat: Negative Working Capital
text: Working capital should be the focus of every Tesla article you read in the next four weeks between now and Tesla's first quarter-end.  Of course it won't be--and that's what keeps it fun--but Musk let the genie out of the bottle with his profit warning last week.

title: Amazon And Tesla Change Business Models
text: Amazon opens stores, as Tesla closes them—One of the two must be doing the wrong thing.

title: Tesla's China profit potential in doubt: Morgan Stanley
text: Jen Rogers, Rick Newman and Myles Udland of Yahoo Finance discuss Tesla's challenges and Adam Jonas of Morgan Stanely voicing concerns.

title: Elon Musk tweets about Tesla truck that may be "too futuristic"
text: Elon Musk tweets there will be a futuristic Tesla pick-up truck announced later this year.

title: Investors would not want to remove Elon Musk as CEO of Tesla, says managing director
text: Jed Dorscheimer of Canaccord Genuity and Ed Lee of the New York Times join CNBC's "Power Lunch" to talk about what Tesla would look like without Elon Musk as CEO after a major shareholder said Musk doesn't need to be CEO.

title: Tesla off to rocky start to the year with surprise store closings
text: Tesla Inc. Chief Executive Officer Elon Musk caught many employees by surprise with his announcement last week that the electric-car maker would close most stores and shift to online-only sales. Bloomberg's Dana Hull reports on Tesla's rocky start to the year. She speaks on "Bloomberg Technology."

title: Tesla workers losing confidence in Elon Musk
text: Jen Rogers, Melody Hahm and Myles Udland of Yahoo Finance discuss a survey that suggests Tesla employees are losing confidence in Elon Musk; the decision at Goldman Sachs to relax the office dress code and reports that Kylie Jenner is now a billionaire.

text: James Anderson, Baillie Gifford partner and portfolio manager, discusses his views on Tesla Inc. the current investment environment with Bloomberg's Ed Hammond on "Bloomberg Markets: The Close."

title: How Tesla's new crossover could hurt Model 3 demand
text: Tesla Inc. will soon unveil its Model Y crossover vehicle, and that’s prompting concerns about a potential cannibalization of sales of the Model 3. Cathie Wood, Ark Invest chief executive officer and chief investment officer, discusses with Bloomberg's Emily Chang on "Bloomberg Technology."

text: Alexa Keenan of Yahoo Finance reports on Tesla's new Model Y and the company's decision to switch to an online only sales model.

text: Also, Tom Jones, former NASA astronaut, discusses the SpaceX launch and what it means for  the future of space travel.

title: Tesla will unveil the Model Y crossover on March 14th
text: Tesla is following up a very busy February with an even more hectic March. Elon Musk has announced that his brand will unveil the long-promised Model Y crossover at the LA Design Studio on March 14th. On top of that, you can expect the first "v3.0" Supercharger station to switch on March 6th at 8PM Pacific. Musk didn't provide more clues beyond that, but you might already have an idea as to what to expect.

title: Tesla closing stores and moving all sales online
text: Alexis Keenan, Melody Hahm and Dan Roberts of Yahoo Finance discuss what Tesla closing dealerships and moving to online only sales means for Tesla customers.

title: Tesla to unveil new SUV
text: Morning Business Outlook: Gymboree and its brands are being eyed by the Children’s Place after filing for bankruptcy; Tesla will unveil its model Y SUV on March 14.

title: SpaceX tests craft to carry humans
text: SpaceX and NASA's successful launch of Crew Dragon gets Elon Musk one step closer to his goal of enabling humans to live on other planets

title: Tesla's $35,000 Model 3: Brilliant Move Or Hail Mary?
text: After the market closed on Thursday, February 28, Tesla’s Elon Musk announced that the company would be selling a $35,000 Standard Range version of the Model 3, closing almost all of its stores and having all cars ordered online.

title: Tesla short seller on Elon Musk's challenges
text: Accipiter Capital Founder Gabe Hoffman, who holds a short position with $TSLA, says Tesla faces a severe cash crunch and inventory problem. He adds that Elon Musk may have broken security laws again. Gabe joins Yahoo Finance's Jackie DeAngelis.

text: From wrangling with the SEC, to announcing a $35,000 Model 3, Tesla CEO Elon Musk had quite an eventful week. Here's a recap.

title: Tesla introduces Model 3 for $35K
text:
Emily McCormick of Yahoo Finance discusses the latest announcements from Tesla.
Tesla unveils standard Model 3, shifts sales to online-only: Tesla (TSLA) just made good on its promise to offer a standard Model 3 vehicle with a $35,000 price tag.

title: Tesla rolling out less expensive Model 3, closes showrooms
text: Rick Newman of Yahoo Finance reports on Elon Musk's announcement that Tesla is unveiling a more affordable Model 3, will be closing stores, switching to an online sales model and expects that Tesla will not be profitable this year.

title: Tesla Bear Johnson warns "Demand Problem" may be behind changes
text: Gordon Johnson, analyst at Vertical Group, examines announcements from Tesla Inc. on a $35,000 Model 3 vehicle, price cuts for the Models S and Model X, and a shift to online sales. He speaks with Bloomberg's Jonathan Ferro on "Bloomberg Markets: The Open."

text: Morning Business Outlook: Elon Musk says Tesla's long-awaited Model 3 has finally arrived and ready for purchase at $35,000

title: Tesla won't be able to shift sales entirely online, says former GM executive
text: Tesla is phasing out its physical dealerships across the country and trying to shift sales to online. The company also announced that they will sell the Model 3 at $35,000. Musk says he expects to sell half a million Model 3 cars worldwide.

title: Tesla "Ripping the Band-Aid Off" in move to online sales, Ives says
text: Dan Ives, managing director at Wedbush Securities, discusses the move by Tesla Inc. to focus on online sales and the $35,000 price point for the Model 3. He speaks on "Bloomberg Daybreak: Americas."

title: Oppenheimer analyst on Tesla $35K Model 3: This is a milestone for the industry
text: Tesla is phasing out its physical dealerships across the country and trying to shift sales to online. The company also announced that they will sell the Model 3 at $35,000. Musk says he expects to sell half a million Model 3 cars worldwide. Colin Rusch, managing director and senior research analyst at Oppenheimer, joins "Squawk Box" by phone to explain how he's approaching the stock.
